mediaNotes: A single "flight" call given by an adult that came within ten feet. A second adult about twenty feet behind it calls in the background of this recording toward the end.

Natural vocalizations (three cuts) from a juvenile that has been present for at least a few days.

The first cut contains only two "flight" calls given from the ground. In keeping with Macaulay recommendations, the minute-long silence between the calls is preserved. The second flight call is at the 1:00 mark. There is some wind interference in the second cut.

Like many LeConte's Sparrows I've encountered, this one prove to be quite curious, coming within a few feet to get a closer look at this strange creature invading its habitat, relying on the cover of the grasses.
At 9:58, weak, wavering, relatively low pitched noises that may also be Le Conte's Sparrow, perhaps an interaction at nest.

mediaNotes: Natural vocalizations (although likely provoked by my presence). Two cuts from the same adult (the one in the attached picture). The calls degrade into a "chup" I have not previously heard from this species, closer to the typical Lincoln's Sparrow calls than anything I have ever heard from LCSP. The flight calls in the second cut also nicely display the plasticity of these calls when not normalized as they likely are during noctural migration.
LeConte's Sparrow vocalizing at Sax-Zim Bog, MN
"Natural" vocalizations in the sense that playback was not used, but clearly given in agitation at my presence.
